    {
      "id": "c85369058c6b21a2699ef56d61a8bf3e09b442c1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 192,
        "name": "Brian Behlendorf",
        "email": "behlendorf1@llnl.gov",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-11-03 22:21:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nI disagree.  This isn't what I would consider simpler nor does it actually work.\n\nThe original patch was carefully designed such that the entire expected prototype was explicit.  Thus you will get a build error when assigning it to an incompatible type.  In the updated patch your just casting the first argument which might get you a harmless warning...  if your lucky.\n\nAdditionally, flagging the variable as unused by gcc will suppress the the spurious warning resulting in a nice clean check.  Ideally, all of these checks should yield the exact same results when run with -Werror.  This avoids the issue when the upstream gcc developers promote an error to a warning which they are prone to do.\n\nPlease, unless you have the exact kernel in question to test against it's probably best not to 'clean up' some of these proposed compatibility changes.  You need to use the original version of this patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "0bb20a6f72bd900cf4d77b5f55857bb7f986104a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 143,
        "name": "Yang Sheng",
        "email": "ys@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "ys"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-08 17:21:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nPatch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nI disagree. This isn't what I would consider simpler nor does it actually work.\n\nThe original patch was carefully designed such that the entire expected prototype was explicit. Thus you will get a build error when assigning it to an incompatible type. In the updated patch your just casting the first argument which might get you a harmless warning... if your lucky.\n\n--Yes, you are right. I forgot to set -Werror for this check.\n\nAdditionally, flagging the variable as unused by gcc will suppress the the spurious warning resulting in a nice clean check. Ideally, all of these checks should yield the exact same results when run with -Werror. This avoids the issue when the upstream gcc developers promote an error to a warning which they are prone to do.\n\n--the set-but-unuse warning will not present on my patch since the variable already be used. \n\nPlease, unless you have the exact kernel in question to test against it's probably best not to 'clean up' some of these proposed compatibility changes. You need to use the original version of this patch.\n\n--I'll update this patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
